'''Kibbutz Gezer Field''' was the home ground for [[Israel]]i [[baseball]] teams [[Modi'in Miracle]] and [[Bet Shemesh Blue Sox]] in the [[Israel Baseball League]].<ref>{{Cite book|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XEw1AwAAQBAJ|title = Pitching in the Promised Land: A Story of the First and Only Season in the Israel Baseball League|last = Pribble|first = Aaron|date = 2011-04-01|publisher = U of Nebraska Press|isbn = 9780803268333|language = en}}</ref> It is located in [[Kibbutz]] [[Gezer, Israel|Gezer]].<ref name="directions">[http://www.israelbaseballleague.com/tickets/directions/ Directions to Kibbutz Gezer Field] at israelbaseballleague.com, URL accessed December 12, 2009. [https://www.webcitation.org/5lyqP636B Archived] 12/12/09</ref>

The field is one of the few regulation baseball fields in Israel.<ref>[https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0013_0_12954.html]</ref> Construction of the field in 1983, funded by American donors, took six weeks. The first game was played within a few months. A backstop, covered benches for players and a refreshment stand were added at a later date. In 1989, a scoreboard and outfield fence were erected for the [[Maccabiah]] Games.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/23/style/out-there-kibbutz-gezer-king-solomon-s-nines.html|title = OUT THERE: KIBBUTZ GEZER; King Solomon's Nines|last = Greenberg|first = Joel|date = 1992-08-23|newspaper = The New York Times|issn = 0362-4331|access-date = 2016-04-14}}</ref>

